[4
Date: 15 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP [edited
<http://www.nandotimes.com/nation/story/141374p-1404662c.html>

Second Florida tabloid worker diagnosed with inhaled anthrax, health
officials say
---------------------
Florida health officials said Monday that a 73-year-old mailroom employee
at a supermarket tabloid in the state has been diagnosed with the inhaled
form of anthrax. [The man "is improving and the public health officials
are encouraged by his
progress," the officials said in a statement. [He has been receiving
treatment for anthrax since he was hospitalized earlier this month for what
was then believed to be pneumonia.
More than 300 AMI employees are expected to undergo a second round of blood
tests to detect the presence of anthrax antibodies. Palm Beach County health
officials said the tests could begin as early as Wednesday. The first round
of blood tests taken last Wednesday on some 400 employees and visitors to
AMI were complete but not yet available.
Earlier, health and postal officials said a small amount of anthrax spores
was found in a Postal Service mail sorting facility in Boca Raton. The
building handles mail for American Media. Nasal swabs of 30 workers at the
facility came back negative for anthrax, Postal Inspector Manny Gonzalez
said.
[Byline: Amanda Riddle
